## Summary

The security fix in commit `e28db3e` corrected `RequestController.php` (Admin) and `RMAController.php` (Shop) to use randomised filenames when storing RMA attachments. The same vulnerability pattern still exists in `RMAImageRepository.php`.

## Vulnerable Code

**`packages/Webkul/RMA/src/Repositories/RMAImageRepository.php` — line 27:**

```php
public function manageImages($requestImages, $rma): void
{
    foreach ($requestImages as $itemImage) {
        $this->create([
            'rma_id' => $rma->id,
            'path'   => $itemImage->getClientOriginalName(), // ⚠️ attacker-controlled
        ]);
    }

    $this->uploadImages($requestImages, $rma);
}
```

`getClientOriginalName()` returns whatever filename the client supplied in the HTTP multipart request — it is fully attacker-controlled. A filename like `../../config/database.php` would be stored in the `path` column as-is.

## What Was Already Fixed (for reference)

In `e28db3e`, `RequestController.php` was changed from:
```php
$filename = $file->getClientOriginalName();
$path = $file->storeAs('rma-conversation/'.$storedMessage->id, $filename);
```
to:
```php
$extension = MimeTypes::getDefault()->getExtensions($file->getMimeType())[0] ?? null;
$path = $file->storeAs(
    'rma-conversation/'.$storedMessage->id,
    Str::random(40).($extension ? '.'.$extension : '')
);
```

The same treatment is needed in `RMAImageRepository::manageImages()`.

## Suggested Fix

```php
use Illuminate\Support\Str;
use Symfony\Component\Mime\MimeTypes;

public function manageImages($requestImages, $rma): void
{
    foreach ($requestImages as $itemImage) {
        $extension = MimeTypes::getDefault()->getExtensions($itemImage->getMimeType())[0] ?? null;
        $this->create([
            'rma_id' => $rma->id,
            'path'   => Str::random(40).($extension ? '.'.$extension : ''),
        ]);
    }

    $this->uploadImages($requestImages, $rma);
}
```

## Files

- `packages/Webkul/RMA/src/Repositories/RMAImageRepository.php` — line 27
- Fixed equivalent: `packages/Webkul/Admin/src/Http/Controllers/Sales/RMA/RequestController.php` — line 172 (post `e28db3e`)

Bagisto Version:
2.4.4
Issue Description:
The updateItems method in Cart.php is missing the actual quantity update logic. 
The method body was replaced with only log statements, causing cart quantity 
updates to silently fail and revert to the original value.
Steps to Reproduce:
1. Add a product to cart
2. Change the quantity using + or - buttons
3. Click "Update Cart"
4. Quantity reverts to original value
Expected Result:
Cart quantity should update to the new value.
Actual Result:
PUT request to /api/checkout/cart returns 200 OK with old quantity. 
Cart quantity reverts to original value.
Suggested Fix:

public function updateItems(array $data): bool|\Exception
{
    foreach ($data['qty'] as $itemId => $quantity) {
        $item = $this->cartItemRepository->find($itemId);

        if (! $item) {
            continue;
        }

        if (
            ! $item->product->getTypeInstance()->isStockable()
            || ! $item->product->getTypeInstance()->haveSufficientQuantity((int) $quantity)
        ) {
            $this->itemsWithErrors[] = [
                'message' => trans('shop::app.checkout.cart.index.quantity.inventory-warning'),
            ];

            continue;
        }

        $item->quantity = $quantity;

        $this->cartItemRepository->update(['quantity' => $quantity], $itemId);
    }

    $this->collectTotals();

    return true;
}
